body:
Trying to find the interface names of all non-loopback interfaces. The input data, from `ip -j link`:

```sh
# input data: link.json
[
  {
    "ifname": "lo",
    "flags": [
      "LOOPBACK",
      "UP"
    ]
  },
  {
    "ifname": "enp0s13f0u1u1",
    "flags": [
      "BROADCAST",
      "UP"
    ]
  }
]
```

My first attempt, with a simple `select`, creates duplicate output:

```sh
# fail: output is duplicated, we need map_values
jq -r ".[] | select (.flags[] | contains(\"LOOPBACK\") | not)" link.json
{
  "ifname": "lo",
  "flags": [
    "LOOPBACK",
    "UP"
  ]
}
{
  "ifname": "enp0s13f0u1u1",
  "flags": [
    "BROADCAST",
    "UP"
  ]
}
{
  "ifname": "enp0s13f0u1u1",
  "flags": [
    "BROADCAST",
    "UP"
  ]
}
```


After [some](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42746828/jq-how-to-query-for-array-values-that-dont-contain-text-foo) [googling](https://github.com/jqlang/jq/discussions/3028) I figured that I need to use `map_values` to prevent the duplicates. This seems to give an unexpected result when `not` is added to the pipeline.

```sh
# getting closer: output is not duplicated, but the filter is the opposite of what we want
jq -r "map_values(select (.flags[] | contains(\"LOOPBACK\")))" link.json 
[
  {
    "ifname": "lo",
    "flags": [
      "LOOPBACK",
      "UP"
    ]
  }
]
```

When `not` is added to this pipeline, I expect to get the "opposite" of the previous output. In particular the "lo" device from the previous query should not be present. So this is unexpected:

```sh
# "lo" device is not filtered, is this a bug?
jq -r "map_values(select (.flags[] | contains(\"LOOPBACK\") | not))" link.json 
[
  {
    "ifname": "lo",
    "flags": [
      "LOOPBACK",
      "UP"
    ]
  },
  {
    "ifname": "enp0s13f0u1u1",
    "flags": [
      "BROADCAST",
      "UP"
    ]
  }
]
```
